04438nam a22005415i 9780804766357DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20221993cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047663577 a10.1515/97808047663572doi  a(DE-B1597)581384  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHD58.7 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a305.5/2/0951952231 aJanelli, Roger L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Capitalism :bThe Social and Cultural Construction of a South Korean Conglomerate /cRoger L. Janelli, Dawnhee Yim. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tIntroduction -- tONE Representations of Korean Culture -- tTWO Representations of South Korean Political Economy -- tTHREE The Bourgeoisie and Their Ideology -- tFOUR Control from the Top -- tFIVE Control at the Middle -- tSIX Responses from Below 1: International and South Korean Political Economy -- tSEVEN Responses from Below II: Working Conditions -- tConclusions -- tBibliography -- tRomanizations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis pathbreaking work extends the boundaries of contemporary anthropological research by presenting in one cohesive, meticulously researched work: an original theoretical perspective on the relationships between the cultural, political, and economic dimensions of a large modern business organization; the first anthropological work on South Korean management and its white-collar workers, in a case study of one of South Korea's "big four" conglomerates; and an innovative delineation of how modern business practices are enmeshed in past and present, structure and agency, and local and international systems." "Based largely on the author's nine months of participant-observation in the offices of one of South Korea's largest conglomerates (with annual sales of about $15 billion and approximately 80,000 employees), the book is also enriched by the author's previous fieldwork in rural Korea, where many of the conglomerate's white-collar personnel spent their formative years. These vantage points are used to explore constructions of "traditional" Korean culture and transformations of cultural knowledge prompted by new political-economic conditions, and how both inform practices prevailing in the large conglomerates - and ultimately shape South Korea's capitalism." "The work focuses on South Korea's new middle class. It explains how office workers' identities and often contradictory interests present them with choices between alternative interpretations and actions affecting both themselves and their conglomerates. Much attention is paid to ideological and more coercive means of controlling white-collar employees, to subordinates' strategies of resistance, and to ways in which cultural understandings and moral claims inform the assessment and pursuit of material advantage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aCapitalismzKorea (South). 0aCorporate culturezKorea (South). 0aElite (Social sciences)zKorea (South). 0aIndustrial managementzKorea (South). 0aMiddle classzKorea (South). 4aAnthropology -- Asia. 4aBusiness -- Organizations and Management Theory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aYim, Dawnhee, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476635740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804766357423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804766357/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles